Ecological Niche Models

Model fitting

Model fitting is the heart of any SDM application. Many different algorithms are available to fit the relationship between occurrence records and environmental predictors.

Generalised linear models

Generalised linear model (GLM) is a typical parametric regression algorithm that can fit linear, quadratic or higher polynomial terms and interactions between predictors.

# load a vector defining global landmasses and crop to the Iberia Peninsula extent
world <- shapefile("Data/vectorShapefiles/globalLandmass/world.shp")
IberianExtent <- extent(-15, 5, 25, 46)
iberianLandMass <- crop(world, IberianExtent)

# read presence / absence datasets for an intertidal species
absences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Kelp-monitoring-absent.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Kelp-monitoring-presence.csv", sep = ";")

# plot the distribution of records
plot(iberianLandMass, col = "gray", border = "gray", main = "Distribution records", axes = TRUE)
points(absences, add = TRUE, cex = 0.75, pch = 19, col = "#3296BA")
points(presences, add = TRUE, cex = 0.75, pch = 19, col = "#BA323F")

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# get raster layers and stack into a unique object
temMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Surface Pred LtMax.tif")
nutrients <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/Nitrate Surface Pred Mean.tif")
envConditions <- stack(temMax, nutrients)

# mask rasters to coastline regions (intertidal species) and crop to the region of interest
coastline <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/CoastLine.tif")
envConditions <- mask(envConditions, coastline)
envConditions <- crop(envConditions, IberianExtent)
plot(envConditions)

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# extract environmental values and make an object with all information to model
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, absences, envConditions)

# fit a binomial GLM to the dataset
model <- trainGLM(modelData)

# predict and map the distribution with the GLM over a raster stack
map <- predict(envConditions, model, type = "response")
plot(iberianLandMass, col = "gray", border = "gray", main = "Habitat suitability map", axes = TRUE)
plot(map, col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"), add = TRUE)

Pseudo-absence data

If true absence data is not available, but one wants to fit an ecological niche model, pseudo-absence data can be generated.

# generate pseudo-absences
pAbsences <- pseudoAbsences(envConditions, presences, n = 100)

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Maximum Entropy

Maxent only uses presence data and the algorithm compares the locations of where a species has been found to all the environments that are available in the study region.

# load a presence dataset of a Mediterranean coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers of temperatures, oxygen and productivity
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
oxygen <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/DissolvedMolecularOxygen Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")
productivity <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")

# stack layers to generate a unique object
envConditionsPresent <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, oxygen, productivity)

# rename layers for simplicity
names(envConditionsPresent) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "oxygen", "productivity")
S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# crop layers to the European extent and plot
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 50)
envConditionsPresent <- crop(envConditionsPresent, europeanExtent)
plot(envConditionsPresent)

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envConditionsPresent, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envConditionsPresent)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData)

# predict with Maxent to raster stack
mapPresent <- predict(model, envConditionsPresent, type = "logistic")
S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot prediction of suitable habitats
plot(mapPresent, col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"), main = "Predicted suitable habitats")

Model transferability

Model transferability is the process of transferring a model to a new dataset.

Temporal transferability

Temporal transferability is the task of predicting to a distinct time than where the model was trained.

# load layers of temperatures, oxygen and productivity
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/RCP85/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/RCP85/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
oxygen <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/RCP85/DissolvedMolecularOxygen Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")
productivity <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/RCP85/TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto Benthic Mean Pred Mean.tif")

# stack layers to generate a unique object and rename
envConditionsFuture <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, oxygen, productivity)
S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Predictor layers must have the same name for proper transferability.

# compare layer names
names(envConditionsPresent)
## [1] "tempMin"      "tempMax"      "oxygen"       "productivity"
names(envConditionsFuture)
## [1] "OceanTemperature.Benthic.Mean.Pred.LtMin"          
## [2] "OceanTemperature.Benthic.Mean.Pred.LtMax"          
## [3] "DissolvedMolecularOxygen.Benthic.Mean.Pred.Mean"   
## [4] "TotalPrimaryProductionPhyto.Benthic.Mean.Pred.Mean"
# change layer names for them to match
names(envConditionsFuture) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "oxygen", "productivity")

# crop layers to the European extent
envConditionsFuture <- crop(envConditionsFuture, europeanExtent)

# predict an map with Maxent for a differenttime period
mapRCP85 <- predict(model, envConditionsFuture, type = c("logistic"))
plot(mapRCP85, col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"), main = "Predicted suitable habitats")

# plot difference in habitat suitability
diffRCP85 <- mapRCP85 - mapPresent
plot(diffRCP85, main = "Difference in suitablity (RCP85)", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "RdBu"))

Spatial transferability

Spatial transferability is the task of predicting to a distinct region than where the model was trained.

# load a presence dataset for an invasive species
presences <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Undaria pinnatifida")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# plot the distribution of records

Spatial transferability

Spatial transferability is the task of predicting to a distinct region than where the model was trained.

# Open and stack raster layers
tempMin <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMin.tif")
tempMax <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/OceanTemperature Benthic Mean Pred LtMax.tif")
nitrate <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/Climate/Present/Nitrate Surface Pred Mean.tif")
envConditionsPresent <- stack(tempMin, tempMax, nitrate)

# mask layers to the coastal region, and then rename
coastline <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/CoastLine.tif")
envConditionsPresent <- mask(envConditionsPresent, coastline)
names(envConditionsPresent) <- c("tempMin", "tempMax", "Nitrate")
S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# crop and plot layers to the native extent
nativeExtent <- extent(115, 155, 20, 50)
envConditionsPresentNative <- crop(envConditionsPresent, nativeExtent)
plot(envConditionsPresentNative)

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# crop layers to the Invasive European extent
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 75)
envConditionsPresentInvasive <- crop(envConditionsPresent, europeanExtent)
plot(envConditionsPresentInvasive)

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envConditionsPresentNative, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envConditionsPresentNative)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = NULL)

# predict with Maxent to the different regions
mapNative <- predict(model, envConditionsPresentNative, type = c("logistic"))
mapEurope <- predict(model, envConditionsPresentInvasive, type = c("logistic"))
S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot suitable habitats for native extent
plot(mapNative, main = "Native habitats of U. pinnatifida", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"))

S4 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot suitable habitats for invasive extent
plot(mapEurope, main = "Invasive habitats of U. pinnatifida", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"))
